text: simulate_track() function generates simulated movement trajectories based existing set tracks. offers three distinct movement models—Directed, Constrained, Unconstrained—representing varying levels constraint movement patterns. flexibility allows users model scenarios reflecting biological environmental constraints, directed movement towards resources, movement along geographical features, free exploratory behavior. Directed model constrained, simulating trajectories follow specific direction based original track’s angular orientation. aims maintain consistent overall direction minor deviations reflect natural variability. model useful scenarios movement highly directional, animal navigating toward known resource. Constrained model represents correlated random walk, movement strictly directional influenced certain angular linear properties original track. model allows random exploration retaining characteristics original movement pattern. suitable situations animals navigate limited knowledge surroundings, navigating within bounded area without specific destination. Unconstrained model provides flexibility, simulating trajectories represent exploratory dispersal behavior without directional bias. based fully random walk starting direction randomly determined simulation. model appropriate scenarios animals moving unfamiliar homogeneous environments. simulate_track() function requires several arguments define simulation process. data argument specifies input track R object. nsim argument defines number simulations run, default value 1000 specified. number represents recommended minimum ensure stable reliable estimation p-values, particularly assessing statistical significance observed trajectory features. Using fewer simulations may result imprecise biased p-value estimates due insufficient sampling null distribution. model argument determines type movement model used, can “Directed”, “Constrained”, “Unconstrained”, default “Unconstrained” provided. function ensures simulations applied trajectories least four steps, calculating standard deviations angles step lengths—essential simulation process—feasible shorter trajectories. cases tracks short, user advised use subset_track() function exclude tracks simulation process. simulate_track() function returns track simulation R object, list simulated trajectories. simulation stored separately, providing users flexibility visualize, analyze, compare simulations original tracks evaluate movement constraints explore alternative movement hypotheses. approach particularly useful testing paleoecological paleoethological hypotheses, assessing whether observed movement patterns consistent group behavior, resource-driven navigation, independent exploratory movement.

Unlike DTW, focuses pointwise alignment, Fréchet distance measures similarity assessing closely two paths follow entire length. approach often illustrated analogy person walking dog leash, can adjust speed independently must remain connected. particularly effective comparing trajectories overall path shape matters, migration routes, travel paths, animal tracks. "None" option compares trajectories , "Centroid" alignment shifts trajectories centroids, eliminating positional differences preserving shape. "Origin" option aligns trajectories starting points, making comparisons independent absolute positions. alignment methods ensure comparisons based movement patterns rather arbitrary spatial differences. Specifically, matrix DTW_distance_metric_p_values Frechet_distance_metric_p_values provided, containing p-values pairwise distances obtained comparing observed tracks generated simulations. DTW_metric_p_values_combined Frechet_metric_p_values_combined elements report overall p-value, summarizing significance similarity tracks considering simulated datasets. Moreover, output includes DTW_distance_metric_simulations Frechet_distance_metric_simulations, list matrices similarity metrics calculated simulated dataset. comprehensive output structure allows users thoroughly evaluate whether observed similarity trajectories greater expected random conditions, providing robust statistical support analyses. combination flexible alignment options, statistical testing, compatibility simulated datasets makes functions highly valuable investigating animal movement patterns, testing hypotheses track similarity, assessing accuracy simulations.

title: QuAnTeTrack
text: track_intersection() function designed detect quantify unique intersections real movement trajectories, helping identify behavioral interactions coordinated movement, chasing, random exploration. comparing actual tracks simulated trajectories generated simulate_track() function, users can statistically assess whether observed intersections occur less frequently expected random conditions. input function track R object. statistical testing desired, test argument must set TRUE track simulation R object provided via sim argument. function offers several options modifying starting positions simulated tracks, controlled origin.permutation argument. set "None", simulated trajectories retain original starting points, making comparable actual data without spatial modification. "Min.Box" option randomly places starting points simulated tracks within minimum bounding box surrounding original starting points, simulating movement within defined area. "Conv.Hull" option provides precise alternative placing simulated tracks within convex hull encompassing original starting points, reflecting actual space occupied tracks. "Custom" option allows users specify area interest providing set coordinates (custom.coord) defining region’s vertices, particularly useful prior knowledge terrain features environmental factors suggests movement may spatially constrained. H1 argument specifies alternative hypothesis tested. set "Lower", function evaluates whether observed intersections significantly fewer generated simulations, may indicate coordinated gregarious movement. set "Higher", tests whether observed intersections significantly greater, indicative predatory chasing interactions. Users must provide value H1 test argument set TRUE. output track_intersection() function track intersection R object provides comprehensive assessment tracks intersect , applicable, intersections compare simulated datasets. core component object Intersection_metric, matrix details number unique intersection points pairs trajectories. test = TRUE, requires track simulation R object generated via simulate_track() provided sim argument, function produces additional outputs aimed statistically evaluating observed intersections. One Intersection_metric_p_values matrix, compares observed intersections derived simulations. p-value matrix indicates proportion simulated datasets intersection counts extreme extreme observed ones, depending selected H1 hypothesis (whether intersections expected fewer frequent random expectation). function also returns Intersection_metric_p_values_combined, single value summarizes overall statistical significance intersection metrics across trajectory pairs. combined p-value provides general indication whether total number intersections observed significantly different generated simulations, either supporting rejecting hypothesis investigation. Additionally, function provides Intersection_metric_simulations, list containing matrices intersection counts simulation iteration. detailed output allows users explore number intersections varies across multiple randomized scenarios, providing deeper insights robustness consistency observed patterns. comparing results simulated tracks, researchers can better evaluate whether observed intersections genuinely meaningful simply result random chance.

what: Why Uncertainty Matters and Sources of Uncertainty
title: Best Practices for Landmarking and Uncertainty Management in QuAnTeTrack
text: Objective, quantitative methods trackway analysis imply false precision inherent uncertainty explicitly measured, reported, managed. Landmarking geometric morphometrics proven highly useful across biology paleontology, reliability depends transparent handling error. Without careful consideration, uncertainty can accumulate multiple sources bias biological interpretations. , main sources uncertainty outlined, together examples may affect results. Anatomical definition landmarks anatomical basis placing landmark vague inconsistently applied, different samplers may digitize slightly different points. example, defining landmark “tip digit” may ambiguous poorly preserved track digit outline rounded. ambiguities inflate variance reduce reproducibility. Sampler/observer effects Experience, training, even fatigue sampler influence results. Intra-observer error (person digitizing multiple times) can lead small systematic differences, inter-observer error (different people digitizing footprint) may reveal much larger discrepancies. affect precision derived metrics step length pace angulation. Preservation sediment effects Substrate conditions strongly influence footprint shape. Erosion can erase edges, infill can distort depth, plastic deformation can shift toe positions. Landmarks digitized areas may reflect true foot anatomy, comparisons across trackways different preservation states can misleading carefully controlled. Image acquisition scaling Digital recording methods—photographs, photogrammetry, laser scanning—introduce biases. Lens distortion, uneven resolution, shadows can obscure features. scale bars tilted aligned footprint plane, subsequent measurements (distances, velocities) biased. Even small scaling errors propagate entire pipeline. Georeferencing orientation trackways digitized field images slabs, orientation relative north, slope, bedding planes must set. Misalignment alters calculated movement directions turning angles. Inconsistent incorrect reference systems can make comparisons across trackways invalid. Interpolation missing footprints parts trackway reconstructed (e.g., missing footprint inferred stride length), uncertainty arises position model-based. Overconfidence interpolated points can bias trajectory smoothness sinuosity measures. Coordinate handling unit conversion Errors coordinate systems (e.g., mixing cm mm, incorrect CRS transformations) propagate derived parameters. Even rounding resampling may bias small-scale metrics step variability. uncertainties highlight importance integrating error evaluation workflow rather treating digitized landmarks exact data.

title: Quantitative Analysis of Tetrapod Trackways
text: Understanding movement behavior extinct tetrapods fundamental aspect palaeobiology, offering glimpse organisms interacted environment . Fossil trackways provide dynamic record locomotor patterns, ecological interactions, even potential social behavior. However, extracting meaningful information ancient tracks requires robust analytical tools capable processing complex datasets. Introducing QuAnTeTrack (Quantitative Analysis Tetrapod Trackways), integrated R package specifically designed facilitate semi-automated extraction palaeobiological insights fossil trackways. versatile tool allows researchers seamlessly convert digitized footprint data analytical objects apply range statistical graphical methods explore locomotor ecological hypotheses. title: Partition anatomical-fidelity uncertainty (simulation-based) — anatomical_error_partitioning
text: "error_partitioning" R object consisting list containing following elements: summary Data frame variance components per variable. Columns: variable, component, variance, percent, \(R^2_c\). Components track (biological), anatomical (within-track simulation variance), Residual (model simulation means). snr Data frame signal--noise ratio per variable. Columns: variable, bio_component (always "track"), bio_var, error_var, SNR. ratio $$SNR = Var(track) / [Var(anatomical) + Var(Residual)].$$ qc Compact quality-control table per variable SNR, qualitative SNR_rating ("weak", "moderate", "strong"), top_component percent, top_percent, \(R^2_c\), observer_note (always "anatomical-" function). models NULL. Placeholder kept consistency observer-inclusive workflow. observer models fitted . analysis_table Long data frame simulated values every track across Monte Carlo runs (variables joined track IDs simulation labels). formulae short note describing simulation-decomposition (within-track anatomical variance simulations, plus random-intercept model simulation means: \(y \sim 1 + (1|track)\); angles handled via sine–cosine). track_names Character vector internal track labels used analysis.

title: Partition anatomical-fidelity uncertainty (simulation-based) — anatomical_error_partitioning
text: function estimates much variability trackway metrics can attributed positional uncertainty track landmarks, rather true biological differences among trackways. asks, essence: "landmarks slightly misplaced error_radius, much affect computed parameters?" trackway, landmarks repeatedly perturbed within specified spatial tolerance, medial trajectory reconstructed, parameters recalculated across Monte Carlo simulations. resulting variance metric decomposed -track component (biological signal) within-track component (anatomical noise). error_radius represents expected imprecision reference-point digitization (e.g., preservation quality, erosion, deformation, subjective landmark interpretation). specifying realistic tolerance, users can evaluate sensitive metric anatomical taphonomic uncertainty identify parameters remain stable despite imperfect preservation. every track simulation, landmarks randomly displaced within circular area radius r, using either uniform model ("uniform") truncated Gaussian X Y SD = r/2 ("gaussian", truncated ±3 SD). perturbed landmark set converted medial trajectory (midpoints consecutive footprints, tps_to_track()), parameters recalculated via track_param(). metric \(Y\), total variance partitioned via law total variance : track (biological) — variance simulation means among tracks; anatomical — mean within-track variances across simulations; Residual — residual random-intercept model simulation means (observer terms simulation-setup). Angular variables (TurnAng, PaceAng) embedded sine–cosine space handle circularity avoid 0°/360° discontinuities (Fisher, 1995). signal--noise ratio quantifies robustness: $$\mathrm{SNR} = \frac{\mathrm{Var}(\mathrm{track})}                 {\mathrm{Var}(\mathrm{anatomical}) + \mathrm{Var}(\mathrm{Residual})}.$$ rule thumb: SNR < 1 — anatomical error exceeds biology (weak); SNR ~ 1–2 — biology anatomical error comparable (moderate); SNR > 2 — biology dominates (strong). compact QC table reports SNR, qualitative rating, top component percent, conditional \(R^2_c\).

code: # Example 1: PaluxyRiver, small jitter (2 cm), uniform noise # Expect relatively stable metrics and higher SNR. set.seed(1) ep_small <- anatomical_error_partitioning(   data         = PaluxyRiver,   error_radius = 0.02,   variables    = c("Distance", "Straightness", "TurnAng"),   n_sim        = 10 ) ep_small$qc #>       variable        SNR SNR_rating top_component top_percent      R2_c #> 1     Distance 2734.80404     strong         track    99.96345 0.9996345 #> 2 Straightness   22.61413     strong         track    95.76525 0.9576525 #> 3      TurnAng 1471.30665     strong         track    99.93208 0.9993208 #>                observer_estimable #> 1 no (anatomical-only, sim-based) #> 2 no (anatomical-only, sim-based) #> 3 no (anatomical-only, sim-based)  # Example 2: PaluxyRiver, larger jitter (8 cm) to see SNR drop # Inflate anatomical uncertainty; SNR should typically decrease. set.seed(1) ep_large <- anatomical_error_partitioning(   data         = PaluxyRiver,   error_radius = 0.08,   variables    = c("Distance", "Straightness", "TurnAng"),   n_sim        = 10 ) ep_large$qc #>       variable        SNR SNR_rating top_component top_percent      R2_c #> 1     Distance 165.040390     strong         track    99.39774 0.9939774 #> 2 Straightness   2.187696     strong         track    68.62938 0.6862938 #> 3      TurnAng  90.802197     strong         track    98.91070 0.9891070 #>                observer_estimable #> 1 no (anatomical-only, sim-based) #> 2 no (anatomical-only, sim-based) #> 3 no (anatomical-only, sim-based)  # Example 3: MountTom subset + Gaussian jitter (3 cm, truncated at ±3 SD) # Demonstrates alternative noise model and a reduced dataset. sbMountTom <- subset_track(   MountTom,   tracks = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 7, 8, 9, 13, 15, 16, 18) ) set.seed(2) ep_gauss <- anatomical_error_partitioning(   data         = sbMountTom,   error_radius = 0.03,   variables    = c("StLength", "sdStLength", "PaceAng"),   n_sim        = 10,   distribution = "gaussian" ) ep_gauss$snr #>              variable bio_component     bio_var    error_var        SNR #> StLength     StLength         track 0.058217558 1.031312e-05 5644.99846 #> sdStLength sdStLength         track 0.001165249 2.973018e-05   39.19415 #> PaceAng       PaceAng         track 0.005343677 2.543369e-04   21.01023  # Example 4: PaluxyRiver with heterogeneous per-track tolerances # Alternate 2 cm / 5 cm across tracks; highlights mixed preservation quality. set.seed(3) rads <- rep(c(0.02, 0.05),             length.out = length(PaluxyRiver$Footprints)) ep_het <- anatomical_error_partitioning(   data         = PaluxyRiver,   error_radius = rads,   variables    = c("TrackWidth", "Sinuosity", "PaceAng"),   n_sim        = 10 ) ep_het$summary #>                variable  component     variance    percent      R2_c #> TrackWidth.1 TrackWidth      track 3.740549e-02 99.7499311 0.9974993 #> TrackWidth.2 TrackWidth anatomical 9.377402e-05  0.2500689 0.9974993 #> TrackWidth.3 TrackWidth   Residual 0.000000e+00  0.0000000 0.9974993 #> Sinuosity.1   Sinuosity      track 3.086845e-03 98.6831363 0.9868314 #> Sinuosity.2   Sinuosity anatomical 4.119198e-05  1.3168637 0.9868314 #> Sinuosity.3   Sinuosity   Residual 0.000000e+00  0.0000000 0.9868314 #> PaceAng.1       PaceAng      track 8.498442e-02 99.7797710 0.9977977 #> PaceAng.2       PaceAng anatomical 1.875734e-04  0.2202290 0.9977977 #> PaceAng.3       PaceAng   Residual 0.000000e+00  0.0000000 0.9977977  # Example 5: Angles only (circular handling via sine–cosine embedding) # Focus on orientation metrics; output includes averaged sin/cos components. set.seed(4) ep_ang <- anatomical_error_partitioning(   data         = PaluxyRiver,   error_radius = 0.04,   variables    = c("TurnAng", "PaceAng"),   n_sim        = 10 ) ep_ang$summary #>           variable  component     variance    percent      R2_c #> TurnAng.1  TurnAng      track 4.283363e-04 99.8192789 0.9981928 #> TurnAng.2  TurnAng anatomical 7.754955e-07  0.1807211 0.9981928 #> TurnAng.3  TurnAng   Residual 0.000000e+00  0.0000000 0.9981928 #> PaceAng.1  PaceAng      track 8.475987e-02 99.7051248 0.9970512 #> PaceAng.2  PaceAng anatomical 2.506750e-04  0.2948752 0.9970512 #> PaceAng.3  PaceAng   Residual 0.000000e+00  0.0000000 0.9970512

Finally, selected movement parameters used input clustering tracks. analysis = "hclust": function performs agglomerative hierarchical clustering pairwise dissimilarity matrix computed working feature matrix (already reflects internal expansion circular variables sine/cosine components, requested transformations z-scaling). algorithm starts track cluster iteratively merges two closest clusters according chosen hclust_method (linkage criterion) single cluster remains. full merge history represented dendrogram can inspected cut desired number clusters. Advantages include distribution-free, since method assume Gaussianity parametric mixture form. also flexible, supporting multiple distance metrics, highly interpretable, dendrogram reveals multiscale clustering structure. addition, number clusters need fixed advance, since can chosen posteriori cutting tree. Disadvantages greedy nature algorithm makes merges irreversible, reassignment possible clusters combined. Results can also sensitive variable scaling, well choice distance metric linkage method. Missing values selected variables cause stats::dist() fail; ensure inputs complete (impute externally) clustering. argument k controls number clusters cut dendrogram. default set 2. NULL, cut made classification returned NULL. Setting k = 1 yields single cluster containing tracks. argument dist_method specifies distance metric used build dissimilarity matrix, passed stats::dist. detailed explanation distance metrics see ?dist. argument hclust_method specifies agglomeration (linkage) method used hierarchical clustering, passed stats::hclust. detailed explanation linkage procedures see ?hclust. analysis = "mclust", clustering performed using finite Gaussian mixture models via Mclust() function mclust package. approach assumes data generated mixture multivariate Gaussian distributions, selects number mixture components covariance parameterization optimizing Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC). Advantages include statistical rigor, automatic model selection, ability capture ellipsoidal cluster shapes. Internally expanded sine cosine components (circular treatment) analysis. measures much direction movement changes step. "sdTurnAng": circular standard deviation turning angles, degrees. Internally expanded sine cosine components analysis respect angular geometry. "Distance": total distance covered track, calculated sum straight-line distances consecutive points (meters). "Length": overall length track, straight-line distance starting ending points (meters). "StLength": Step lengths step track, representing far object moved two consecutive points (meters). "sdStLength": standard deviation step lengths, showing consistent steps length (meters). "Sinuosity": measure track's winding nature, calculated ratio actual track length straight-line distance (dimensionless). "Straightness": straightness track, calculated straight-line distance divided total path length (dimensionless). "Velocity": average velocity track, calculated total distance divided time elapsed first last footprint (meters per second). "sdVelocity": standard deviation velocity, indicating much velocity fluctuates throughout track (meters per second). "MaxVelocity": maximum velocity achieved track, identifying fastest point (meters per second). "MinVelocity": minimum velocity track, identifying slowest point (meters per second). "TrackWidth": Trackway width, .e., lateral spacing left right footprint series (units consistent input coordinates, typically meters). "PaceAng": Pace angulation (degrees), classical ichnological descriptor summarizing angular relation successive steps within trackway. cluster_track() function biological relevance identifying groups tracks similar movement parameters, providing insights ecological behavioral patterns. clustering tracks based characteristics sinuosity, velocity, turning angles (treated circularly via sine/cosine), helps detect movement patterns associated specific behaviors. can reveal tracks potentially made individuals moving together, useful investigating hypotheses gregarious behavior, predation strategies, coordinated movement. what: Test for steady, acceleration, or deceleration along trajectories — mode_velocity
title: Test for steady, acceleration, or deceleration along trajectories — mode_velocity
text: mode_velocity() evaluates trend velocity along trajectory applying Spearman's rank correlation test. function classifies trend "acceleration", "deceleration", "steady" based correlation p-value.

title: Test for steady, acceleration, or deceleration along trajectories — mode_velocity
code: mode_velocity(trackvel)

title: Test for steady, acceleration, or deceleration along trajectories — mode_velocity
text: trackvel track velocity object  element corresponds track contains vector velocity relative stride length data.

title: Test for steady, acceleration, or deceleration along trajectories — mode_velocity
text: list element corresponds trajectory input trackvel contains: correlation: result Spearman correlation test, including correlation coefficient p-value. trend: classification trend "Acceleration", "Deceleration", "Steady" based p-value correlation coefficient. trajectory fewer 3 steps, entry contains message "Less three steps."

title: Test for steady, acceleration, or deceleration along trajectories — mode_velocity
text: mode_velocity() function performs following operations: Spearman's Rank Correlation Test: non-parametric test assesses strength direction monotonic relationship two variables. require assumptions normality data linear relationship velocity step number. uses ranks rather raw values, making robust outliers suitable detecting general trends (acceleration deceleration) velocity data. Function Operation: trajectory trackvel list, function calculates Spearman correlation coefficient associated p-value velocity step number. Based p-value correlation coefficient, classifies trend "acceleration", "deceleration", "steady". trajectory contains fewer 3 steps, function returns message indicating insufficient data correlation analysis. Advantages: non-parametric nature allows flexibility data distributions reduced sensitivity outliers compared parametric tests. Effective detecting monotonic trends (either increasing decreasing) correlation statistically significant. Limitations: May unreliable small sample sizes (e.g., fewer 3 steps), providing potentially non-informative results. capture magnitude change provide detailed insights rate acceleration deceleration. Identifies monotonic trends based statistical significance distinguish different types monotonic relationships (e.g., steady acceleration vs. abrupt changes). Interpretation Results: Acceleration: p-value less 0.05 Spearman correlation coefficient positive. Deceleration: p-value less 0.05 Spearman correlation coefficient negative. Steady: p-value greater equal 0.05, indicating significant monotonic relationship. Usage Considerations: Ensure trajectory trackvel sufficient number steps meaningful analysis. detailed analysis velocity trends, consider complementary methods linear non-linear regression, specialized change point detection techniques.

title: Partition intra- and inter-observer uncertainty (replicate-based) — observer_error_partitioning
text: data track R object, list consisting two elements: Trajectories: list interpolated trajectories, trajectory series midpoints consecutive footprints. Footprints: list data frames containing footprint coordinates, metadata (e.g., image reference, ID), marker indicating whether footprint actual inferred. metadata data frame one row per track (order track_param(data)). Required columns: replica — replicate index within (track, observer). track — biological track ID. observer — observer ID. variables character vector parameters analyze. title: Partition intra- and inter-observer uncertainty (replicate-based) — observer_error_partitioning
text: "error_partitioning" R object consisting list containing following elements: summary Data frame variance components per variable. Columns: variable, component, variance, percent, \(R^2_c\). Components reflect estimable (e.g., track, observer, observer:track, Residual). snr Data frame signal--noise ratio per variable. Columns: variable, bio_component (always "track"), bio_var, error_var, SNR. SNR $$SNR = Var(track) / [Var(observer) + Var(observer:track) + Var(Residual)].$$ qc Compact quality-control table per variable SNR, qualitative SNR_rating ("weak", "moderate", "strong"), top_component percent, top_percent, \(R^2_c\), whether observer term estimable (observer_estimable). analysis_table Data frame used analysis: selected variables joined metadata (columns typically include replica, track, observer). models Fitted mixed-effects models used extract variance components. linear variables, entry stores lmer fit variance components. angular variables, entry list separate sin cos fits. formulae Model formula(e) per variable. angular variables, list containing sin cos formulas. track_names Character vector internal track labels used analysis.

title: Partition intra- and inter-observer uncertainty (replicate-based) — observer_error_partitioning
text: function partitions variability selected metric components attributable biology (consistent differences among tracks) human sampling process: differences observers (inter-observer sampling error) differences repeated digitizations observer (intra-observer sampling error). Use audit reproducibility across people sessions, identify metrics remain stable despite digitizes , prioritize protocol changes (clearer landmark definitions, training, calibration) reduce measurement noise. Metrics whose variability dominated biological signal interpretable downstream (testing, clustering, classification), whereas dominated observer/replica effects warrant caution methodological refinement. metric model fits random intercepts track, observer, observer:track interaction. Replicate--replicate scatter within (observer, track) cell contributes residual (intra-observer sampling error). Random terms appear single level dropped automatically. $$y \sim 1 + (1|track) + (1|observer) + (1|observer:track).$$ Angular variables (TurnAng, PaceAng) handled sine–cosine space respect circularity avoid 0°/360° discontinuities: random-effects structure fit separately \(\sin(\theta)\) \(\cos(\theta)\), two variance decompositions averaged (Fisher, 1995). Robustness summarized signal--noise ratio $$SNR = \frac{Var(track)}{Var(observer) + Var(observer:track) + Var(Residual)}.$$ rule thumb: SNR < 1 — observer/replicate error exceeds biology; metric weak; SNR ~ 1–2 — biology error comparable; moderate robustness; SNR > 2 — biology dominates; strongly robust. compact QC table reports SNR, qualitative rating, top variance component percent, conditional \(R^2_c\); also flags whether inter-observer term estimable (>1 level). Practical designs: Full inter + intra: provide multiple observers multiple replicates per observer. observer observer:track estimable; replicate scatter residual. Intra-: set metadata$observer value rows provide replica >1 levels. track remains; replicate scatter residual. Inter-: set metadata$replica single level supply multiple observers. observer estimable; residual still represents replicate-level noise (present). Note estimates can sensitive designs highly unbalanced sample sizes small; singular fits (random variances /near zero) may occur (REML) interpreted cautiously. function simulate anatomical landmark jitter; quantify sensitivity landmark placement (e.g., preservation, landmark ambiguity), use anatomical_error_partitioning(). replicated digitizations (across observers /replicate attempts) must bundled together single data object (.e., file), replicate represented track entry. split replicates across multiple files/objects, track_param(data) metadata must align one row per replicate order.

title: Partition intra- and inter-observer uncertainty (replicate-based) — observer_error_partitioning
text: Humberto G. Ferrón humberto.ferron@uv.es Macroevolution Functional Morphology Research Group (www.macrofun.es) Cavanilles Institute Biodiversity Evolutionary Biology Calle Catedrático José Beltrán Martínez, nº 2 46980 Paterna - Valencia - Spain Phone: +34 (9635) 44477

title: Partition intra- and inter-observer uncertainty (replicate-based) — observer_error_partitioning
code: # Example 1: Full partition (inter + intra via residual) # Model: (1|track) + (1|observer) + (1|observer:track). # Var(track)=biology; Var(observer)=inter-observer; # Var(observer:track)=observer×track; Residual=intra-observer. tps <- system.file("extdata", "PaluxyRiverObsRep.tps",                    package = "QuAnTeTrack") RL <- rep(c("R","L"), length.out = 34) trks <- tps_to_track(file = tps, scale = 0.004341493,                      R.L.side = RL, missing = FALSE, NAs = NULL)  n  <- length(trks$Trajectories) md <- data.frame(   track    = rep(c("T01","T02"), length.out = n),   observer = ifelse(seq_len(n) <= ceiling(n/2), "obs1", "obs2"),   stringsAsFactors = FALSE ) md$replica <- ave(seq_len(n),                   interaction(md$observer, md$track, drop = TRUE),                   FUN = seq_along) md <- md[, c("replica","track","observer")]  vars <- c("Distance","Straightness","TurnAng","PaceAng") res_full <- observer_error_partitioning(data = trks,                                         metadata = md,                                         variables = vars) res_full$qc #>       variable        SNR SNR_rating top_component top_percent      R2_c #> 1     Distance 14362.3060     strong         track    99.99304 0.9999304 #> 2 Straightness   158.6878     strong         track    99.37378 0.9937378 #> 3      TurnAng  3642.6814     strong         track    99.97256 0.9997673 #> 4      PaceAng   314.5134     strong         track    99.68306 0.9990678 #>   observer_estimable #> 1                yes #> 2                yes #> 3                yes #> 4                yes  # Example 2: Intra-only, single observer; residual = intra-observer md_intra <- md md_intra$observer <- "obs1" res_intra <- observer_error_partitioning(data = trks,                                          metadata = md_intra,                                          variables = vars) res_intra$qc #>       variable        SNR SNR_rating top_component top_percent      R2_c #> 1     Distance 14362.5544     strong         track    99.99304 0.9999304 #> 2 Straightness   158.6867     strong         track    99.37377 0.9937377 #> 3      TurnAng  3643.9188     strong         track    99.97256 0.9997582 #> 4      PaceAng   314.5132     strong         track    99.68306 0.9990678 #>   observer_estimable #> 1       no (1 level) #> 2       no (1 level) #> 3       no (1 level) #> 4       no (1 level)  # Example 3: Inter-only, single replicate; estimates inter-observer md_inter <- md md_inter$replica <- 1L res_inter <- observer_error_partitioning(data = trks,                                          metadata = md_inter,                                          variables = vars) res_inter$qc #>       variable        SNR SNR_rating top_component top_percent      R2_c #> 1     Distance 14362.3060     strong         track    99.99304 0.9999304 #> 2 Straightness   158.6878     strong         track    99.37378 0.9937378 #> 3      TurnAng  3642.6814     strong         track    99.97256 0.9997673 #> 4      PaceAng   314.5134     strong         track    99.68306 0.9990678 #>   observer_estimable #> 1                yes #> 2                yes #> 3                yes #> 4                yes  # Example 4: Circular metrics only (angles via sine–cosine embedding) res_ang <- observer_error_partitioning(data = trks,                                        metadata = md,                                        variables = c("TurnAng","PaceAng")) res_ang$summary #>           variable      component     variance      percent      R2_c #> TurnAng.1  TurnAng observer:track 9.047652e-11 1.974434e-05 0.9997673 #> TurnAng.2  TurnAng       observer 0.000000e+00 0.000000e+00 0.9997673 #> TurnAng.3  TurnAng          track 4.581145e-04 9.997256e+01 0.9997673 #> TurnAng.4  TurnAng       Residual 1.256725e-07 2.742503e-02 0.9997673 #> PaceAng.1  PaceAng observer:track 2.082826e-50 1.531558e-47 0.9990678 #> PaceAng.2  PaceAng       observer 1.524969e-17 1.121350e-14 0.9990678 #> PaceAng.3  PaceAng          track 1.355629e-01 9.968306e+01 0.9990678 #> PaceAng.4  PaceAng       Residual 4.310243e-04 3.169437e-01 0.9990678

code: # Example 1: Simulate tracks using data from the Paluxy River # Default model (Unconstrained movement) simulated_tracks <- simulate_track(PaluxyRiver, nsim = 3) #> Warning: `model` is NULL. Defaulting to 'Unconstrained'.  # Plot simulated tracks with default settings and actual tracks plot_sim(PaluxyRiver, simulated_tracks)   # Example 2: Simulate tracks using the "Directed" model, representing movement toward a # resource simulated_tracks_directed <- simulate_track(PaluxyRiver, nsim = 3, model = "Directed")  # Plot simulated tracks with specific colors and transparency for "Directed" model plot_sim(PaluxyRiver, simulated_tracks_directed,   colours_sim = c("#E69F00", "#56B4E9"),   alpha_sim = 0.4, lwd_sim = 1, colours_act = c("black", "black"), alpha_act = 0.7,   lwd_act = 2 )   # Example 3: Simulate tracks using the "Constrained" model, representing movement along # a feature simulated_tracks_constrained <- simulate_track(PaluxyRiver, nsim = 3, model = "Constrained")  # Plot simulated tracks with a different color scheme and width for "Constrained" model plot_sim(PaluxyRiver, simulated_tracks_constrained,   colours_sim = c("#E69F00", "#56B4E9"),   alpha_sim = 0.6, lwd_sim = 0.1, alpha_act = 0.5, lwd_act = 2 )   # Example 4: Simulate tracks using the "Unconstrained" model (random exploratory # movement) simulated_tracks_unconstrained <- simulate_track(PaluxyRiver, nsim = 3, model = "Unconstrained")  # Plot simulated tracks with default colors and increased transparency for "Unconstrained" # model plot_sim(PaluxyRiver, simulated_tracks_unconstrained,   colours_sim = c("#E69F00", "#56B4E9"),   alpha_sim = 0.2, lwd_sim = 1, colours_act = c("#E69F00", "#56B4E9"), alpha_act = 0.9,   lwd_act = 2 )   # Subsetting trajectories with four or more steps in the Mount Tom dataset sbMountTom <- subset_track(MountTom, tracks = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 7, 8, 9, 13, 15, 16, 18))  # Example 5: Simulate tracks using data from Mount Tom simulated_tracks_mt <- simulate_track(sbMountTom, nsim = 3) #> Warning: `model` is NULL. Defaulting to 'Unconstrained'.  # Plot simulated tracks with default settings and actual tracks from Mount Tom plot_sim(sbMountTom, simulated_tracks_mt)   # Example 6: Simulate tracks using the "Directed" model for Mount Tom simulated_tracks_mt_directed <- simulate_track(sbMountTom, nsim = 3, model = "Directed")  # Plot simulated tracks with specific colors and transparency for "Directed" model for Mount # Tom plot_sim(sbMountTom, simulated_tracks_mt_directed, colours_sim = c(   "#E69F00", "#56B4E9",   "#009E73", "#F0E442", "#0072B2", "#D55E00", "#CC79A7", "#999999", "#F4A300",   "#6C6C6C", "#1F77B4" ), alpha_sim = 0.3, lwd_sim = 1.5, alpha_act = 0.8, lwd_act = 2)   # Example 7: Simulate tracks using the "Constrained" model for Mount Tom simulated_tracks_mt_constrained <- simulate_track(sbMountTom, nsim = 3, model = "Constrained")  # Plot simulated tracks with different color scheme and increased line width for "Constrained" # model plot_sim(sbMountTom, simulated_tracks_mt_constrained, colours_sim = c(   "#E41A1C", "#377EB8",   "#4DAF4A", "#FF7F00", "#F781BF", "#A65628", "#FFFF33", "#8DD3C7", "#FB8072",   "#80BF91", "#F7F7F7" ), alpha_sim = 0.5, lwd_sim = 0.2, alpha_act = 0.6, lwd_act = 2)   # Example 8: Simulate tracks using the "Unconstrained" model for Mount Tom simulated_tracks_mt_unconstrained <- simulate_track(sbMountTom, nsim = 3, model = "Unconstrained")  # Plot simulated tracks with a different color scheme and transparency for "Unconstrained" model plot_sim(sbMountTom, simulated_tracks_mt_unconstrained, colours_sim = c(   "#6BAED6", "#FF7F00",   "#1F77B4", "#D62728", "#2CA02C", "#9467BD", "#8C564B", "#E377C2", "#7F7F7F",   "#BCBD22", "#17BECF" ), alpha_sim = 0.2, lwd_sim = 0.5, colours_act = c(   "#6BAED6",   "#FF7F00", "#1F77B4", "#D62728", "#2CA02C", "#9467BD", "#8C564B", "#E377C2",   "#7F7F7F", "#BCBD22", "#17BECF" ), alpha_act = 1, lwd_act = 2)

title: Plot trajectories colored by velocity or relative stride length — plot_velocity
code: # Example 1: Plot Trajectories Colored by Velocity with Default Settings (MountTom dataset)  # Hip heights for each track in the MountTom dataset H_mounttom <- c(   1.380, 1.404, 1.320, 1.736, 1.364, 1.432, 1.508, 1.768, 1.600, 1.848,   1.532, 1.532, 0.760, 1.532, 1.688, 1.620, 0.636, 1.784, 1.676, 1.872,   1.648, 1.760, 1.612 )  # Calculate velocities using the default Method "A" V_mounttom <- velocity_track(MountTom, H = H_mounttom)  # Plot trajectories colored by velocity plot1 <- plot_velocity(MountTom, V_mounttom, param = "V") print(plot1)   # Example 2: Plot Trajectories Colored by Relative Stride Length with Default Settings # (PaluxyRiver dataset)  # Hip heights for each track in the PaluxyRiver dataset H_paluxyriver <- c(3.472, 2.200)  # Specify different methods for different tracks Method_paluxyriver <- c("A", "B")  # Calculate velocities using specified methods V_paluxyriver <- velocity_track(PaluxyRiver, H = H_paluxyriver, method = Method_paluxyriver)  # Plot trajectories colored by relative stride length plot2 <- plot_velocity(PaluxyRiver, V_paluxyriver, param = "RSL") print(plot2)   # Example 3: Plot Trajectories Colored by Velocity with Custom Line Width and Colors # (MountTom dataset)  # Custom colors and line width custom_colours <- c("blue", "green", "yellow", "red") custom_lwd <- 2  # Plot trajectories with custom colors and line width plot3 <- plot_velocity(MountTom, V_mounttom,   param = "V", lwd = custom_lwd,   colours = custom_colours ) print(plot3)   # Example 4: Plot Trajectories Colored by Relative Stride Length with Custom Line Width # and No Legend (PaluxyRiver dataset)  # Custom colors and line width custom_colours_rsl <- c("purple", "orange", "pink", "gray") custom_lwd_rsl <- 1.5  # Plot trajectories with custom colors, line width, and no legend plot4 <- plot_velocity(PaluxyRiver, V_paluxyriver,   param = "RSL", lwd = custom_lwd_rsl,   colours = custom_colours_rsl, legend = FALSE ) print(plot4)

DTW_distance_metric_p_values (test = TRUE) numeric matrix raw pairwise p-values, computed Monte Carlo tail tests (+1) correction (Phipson & Smyth, 2010): $$p = (1 + \#\{\text{extreme}\}) / (nsim + 1)$$. entry reflects probability observing DTW distance extreme observed one, given null hypothesis difference. title: Similarity metric using Dynamic Time Warping (DTW) — simil_DTW_metric
text: simil_DTW_metric() function calculates similarity trajectories using Dynamic Time Warping (DTW) algorithm dtw package. dtw() function used dist.method argument set "Euclidean" computing local distances points trajectories. DTW aligns two time series minimizing cumulative distance points, creating optimal alignment despite variations length temporal distortions. algorithm constructs distance matrix element represents cost aligning points two series finds warping path matrix minimizes total distance. warping path contiguous monotonic, starting bottom-left corner ending top-right corner (Cleasby et al., 2019). DTW measures non-negative unbounded, larger values indicating greater dissimilarity time series. method used various contexts, including ecological studies analyze cluster trajectory data (Cleasby et al., 2019). Potential limitations biases DTW include sensitivity noise outliers, computational complexity, need appropriate distance metrics. Additionally, DTW may always account structural differences trajectories can biased chosen alignment constraints. DTW can handle trajectories different lengths due elastic nature, trajectories similar lengths can improve accuracy interpretability similarity measure. Similar lengths result meaningful alignment can make computation efficient. trajectories differ significantly length, preprocessing normalization might necessary, careful analysis required understand alignment path. function’s flexibility handling different lengths allows applied various contexts. However, large differences trajectory lengths might introduce potential biases considered interpreting results. function offers three different superposition methods align trajectories DTW() applied: "None": superposition applied. "Centroid": Trajectories shifted align based centroids. "Origin": Trajectories shifted align based starting point. test = TRUE, function can compute p-values comparing observed DTW distances generated set simulated trajectories. p-values calculated individual trajectory pairs entire set trajectories. Pairwise p-values computed Monte Carlo tail test using (+1) correction avoid zero-values (see Phipson & Smyth, 2010): $$p = (1 + \#\{\text{extreme}\}) / (nsim + 1)$$ raw p-values adjusted multiple comparisons across set unique pairwise tests using Benjamini–Hochberg (BH) procedure false discovery rate (FDR) control (Benjamini & Hochberg, 1995). raw BH-adjusted p-value matrices returned output object, allowing users inspect either uncorrected corrected results. addition, global combined p-value provided, summarizing overall deviation null across pairs.

what: Simulate tracks using different models — simulate_track
title: Simulate tracks using different models — simulate_track
text: simulate_track() simulates movement trajectories based original set tracks. Three movement models available simulation, reflecting different levels constraint movement patterns. models can represent biological environmental constraints, movement along coastlines, rivers, towards resources like water food.

title: Simulate tracks using different models — simulate_track
code: simulate_track(data, nsim = NULL, model = NULL)

title: Simulate tracks using different models — simulate_track
text: data track R object, list consisting two elements: Trajectories: list interpolated trajectories, trajectory series midpoints consecutive footprints. Footprints: list data frames containing footprint coordinates, metadata (e.g., image reference, ID), marker indicating whether footprint actual inferred. nsim number simulations run. Defaults 1000 specified. model type movement model use. Options "Directed", "Constrained", "Unconstrained". Defaults "Unconstrained" provided.

title: Simulate tracks using different models — simulate_track
text: track simulation R object consisting list simulated trajectories stored track R objects.

title: Simulate tracks using different models — simulate_track
text: function simulates movement trajectories based following models: Directed: model simulates movement follows specific direction navigating compass (.e., directed walk/allothetic directed walk/oriented path) (Cheung et al., 2007, 2008). trajectory constrained angular linear properties original track, minor deviations allowed reflect natural variability. Angular constraints: trajectory closely follows specific direction, maintaining overall angular orientation original track. Deviations consecutive steps governed angular standard deviation calculated original track using TrajAngles(). Linear constraints: Step lengths constrained mean original track's step lengths, variability allowed according standard deviation step lengths computed TrajStepLengths(). Starting direction: Fixed original direction (overall angular orientation) track. model ideal simulating movement directed toward specific resource constrained natural barriers, relatively fixed direction minor deviations. Constrained: model simulates movement correspond correllated random walk/idiothetic directed walk (Kareiva & Shigesada, 1983), corresponding animal navigating without compass (Cheung et al., 2008), still maintaining certain angular linear characteristics original track. provides flexibility Directed model entirely random like Unconstrained model. Angular constraints: trajectory follow specific direction. Deviations consecutive steps governed angular standard deviation calculated original track using TrajAngles(). Linear constraints: Step lengths constrained mean original track's step lengths, variability allowed according standard deviation step lengths computed TrajStepLengths(). Starting direction: Fixed original direction (overall angular orientation) track. model suitable scenarios movement influenced external constraints allows degree random exploration. Unconstrained: model simulates movement correspond correllated random walk/idiothetic directed walk (Kareiva & Shigesada, 1983), corresponding animal navigating without compass (Cheung et al., 2008), still maintaining certain angular linear characteristics original track. Angular constraints: trajectory follow specific direction. Deviations consecutive steps governed angular standard deviation calculated original track using TrajAngles(). Linear constraints: Step lengths constrained mean original track's step lengths, variability allowed according standard deviation step lengths computed TrajStepLengths(). Starting direction: Randomly determined. model suitable simulating exploratory dispersal behavior open environments, movement random influenced specific constraints. Note: Simulations applied trajectories fewer four steps standard deviations angles step lengths computed short trajectories. Consider using subset_track() function filter tracks four steps. function utilizes trajr package key calculations: TrajGenerate(): Generates new trajectory based random directed movement models, constrained specified parameters. TrajStepLengths(): Calculates step lengths (distances consecutive points) original trajectory. TrajAngles(): Computes angles consecutive segments trajectory, used maintain directional movement constrained models. TrajRotate(): Rotates trajectory specified angle match original direction random angle unconstrained models. TrajTranslate(): Translates simulated trajectory start geographic location original. NISTdegTOradian() function NISTunits package used convert angles degrees radians.

title: Simulate tracks using different models — simulate_track
code: # Example 1: Simulate tracks using data from the Paluxy River # Default model (Unconstrained movement) simulated_tracks <- simulate_track(PaluxyRiver, nsim = 3) #> Warning: `model` is NULL. Defaulting to 'Unconstrained'.  # Example 2: Simulate tracks using the "Directed" model, representing movement # toward a resource (e.g., water source) simulated_tracks_directed <- simulate_track(PaluxyRiver, nsim = 3, model = "Directed")  # Example 3: Simulate tracks using the "Constrained" model, representing movement # along a geographic feature (e.g., coastline) simulated_tracks_constrained <- simulate_track(PaluxyRiver, nsim = 3, model = "Constrained")  # Example 4: Simulate tracks using the "Unconstrained" model (random exploratory movement) simulated_tracks_unconstrained <- simulate_track(PaluxyRiver, nsim = 3, model = "Unconstrained")  # Subsetting trajectories with four or more steps in the MountTom dataset sbMountTom <- subset_track(MountTom, tracks = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 7, 8, 9, 13, 15, 16, 18))  # Example 5: Simulate tracks using data from Mount Tom # Default model (Unconstrained movement) simulated_tracks_mt <- simulate_track(sbMountTom, nsim = 3) #> Warning: `model` is NULL. Defaulting to 'Unconstrained'.  # Example 6: Simulate tracks using the "Directed" model for Mount Tom, representing # directed movement simulated_tracks_mt_directed <- simulate_track(sbMountTom, nsim = 3, model = "Directed")  # Example 7: Simulate tracks using the "Constrained" model for Mount Tom, representing # constrained movement simulated_tracks_mt_constrained <- simulate_track(sbMountTom, nsim = 3, model = "Constrained")  # Example 8: Simulate tracks using the "Unconstrained" model for Mount Tom, representing # random exploratory movement simulated_tracks_mt_unconstrained <- simulate_track(sbMountTom, nsim = 3, model = "Unconstrained")

title: Test for differences in direction means with pairwise comparisons — test_direction
text: test_direction() assesses differences mean direction across tracks using selected circular statistical test. provides two options: parametric Watson–Williams test (default), assumes directions follow von Mises distribution dispersion homogeneous across tracks—assumptions automatically checked testing—non-parametric Watson–Wheeler test, require assumptions. datasets two tracks, function also performs pairwise comparisons identify tracks differ significantly mean direction.

title: Test for differences in direction means with pairwise comparisons — test_direction

Similarity concentrations: Per-track concentration \((\kappa)\) estimated via est.kappa. Large heterogeneity (e.g., \(\max(\kappa)/\min(\kappa) > 2\)) unstable estimates trigger warning, since Watson–Williams test assumes approximately similar concentration across tracks. Statistical Analysis: Watson–Williams (default): Parametric comparison mean directions across tracks (assumes von Mises similar concentration). Watson–Wheeler: Non-parametric k-sample test differences direction. groups \(n < 10\) ties (identical angles), asymptotic chi-squared p-value can unreliable. address , function can compute permutation (Monte-Carlo) p-value Watson–Wheeler statistic (W). permutation = NULL (default), permutation p-value used automatically small samples ties; otherwise, user's choice respected. tiny internal jitter (radians) applied angles ties detected stabilize test; exposed argument. what: Test for differences in velocity means with pairwise comparisons — test_velocity
title: Test for differences in velocity means with pairwise comparisons — test_velocity
text: test_velocity() evaluates differences velocity means across different tracks using specified statistical test. includes options ANOVA, Kruskal-Wallis test, Generalized Linear Models (GLM), checks assumptions normality homogeneity variances. datasets two tracks, performs pairwise comparisons identify specific differences tracks.

title: Test for differences in velocity means with pairwise comparisons — test_velocity
code: test_velocity(data, trackvel, plot = FALSE, analysis = NULL)

title: Test for differences in velocity means with pairwise comparisons — test_velocity
text: data track R object, list consisting two elements: Trajectories: list interpolated trajectories, trajectory series midpoints consecutive footprints. Footprints: list data frames containing footprint coordinates, metadata (e.g., image reference, ID), marker indicating whether footprint actual inferred. trackvel track velocity R object consisting list element corresponds track contains velocity relative stride length data. plot logical value indicating whether plot boxplot velocities track (default FALSE). analysis character string specifying type analysis: "ANOVA", "Kruskal-Wallis", "GLM". Default "ANOVA".

title: Test for differences in velocity means with pairwise comparisons — test_velocity
text: list results statistical analysis diagnostic tests: normality_results: matrix test statistics p-values Shapiro-Wilk test track, rows test statistic p-value, columns track. homogeneity_test: result Levene's test, including p-value homogeneity variances. ANOVA (analysis "ANOVA"): list containing ANOVA table Tukey HSD post-hoc test results. Kruskal_Wallis (analysis "Kruskal-Wallis"): list containing Kruskal-Wallis test result Dunn's test post-hoc results. GLM (analysis "GLM"): summary GLM fit pairwise comparisons. plot (plot TRUE): boxplot velocities track generated displayed.

title: Test for differences in velocity means with pairwise comparisons — test_velocity
text: test_velocity function performs following operations: Condition Testing: Normality: Shapiro-Wilk test normality velocity data within track. Homogeneity Variances: Levene's test equal variances across tracks. Statistical Analysis: ANOVA: Compares mean velocities across tracks, assuming normality homogeneity variances. Includes Tukey's HSD post-hoc test pairwise comparisons. Kruskal-Wallis Test: Non-parametric alternative ANOVA comparing median velocities across tracks assumptions violated. Includes Dunn's test pairwise comparisons. GLM: Generalized Linear Model Gaussian family comparing means ANOVA assumptions met. Pairwise comparisons GLM conducted using estimated marginal means (least-squares means) emmeans package, computes differences group means adjusting multiple comparisons using Tukey’s method. Plotting: plot TRUE, boxplot velocities track generated.

code: tps_to_track(file, scale = NULL, R.L.side, missing = FALSE, NAs = NULL)

title: Transform a *.tps file into a track R object — tps_to_track
text: file *.tps file containing (x,y) coordinates footprints tracks. scale numeric value specifying scale meters per pixel. R.L.side character vector specifying side first footprint track. length vector must equal total number tracks sample. "L": first footprint corresponds left foot. "R": first footprint corresponds right foot. missing logical value indicating whether missing footprints track interpolated: TRUE, FALSE (default). NAs matrix two columns indicating missing footprints interpolated. first column gives number track containing missing footprints, second column gives number footprint missing within track. number rows equal total number missing footprints sample.

title: Transform a *.tps file into a track R object — tps_to_track
text: track R object, list consisting two elements: Trajectories: list trajectories (midpoints consecutive footprints). Includes columns X, Y, IMAGE, ID, Side (set "Medial"). Footprints: list data frames containing footprint coordinates metadata, Side column ("R" "L") missing marker ("Actual" "Inferred").

title: Transform a *.tps file into a track R object — tps_to_track
text: highly recommended *.tps file built using TPS software (Rohlf 2008, 2009). Tracks different number footprints (.e., landmarks) allowed. function transforms coordinates footprints track set trajectory coordinates. point trajectory calculated : $$Point_i(x,y)= (Footprint_i(x,y) + Footprint_{+1}(x,y)/2$$ number points resulting trajectory \(n_{footprints} - 1\). missing set TRUE, missing footprints can interpolated. interpolation based adjacent footprints provided side information.

title: Calculate intersection metrics in tracks — track_intersection
text: data track R object, list consisting two elements: Trajectories: list interpolated trajectories, trajectory series midpoints consecutive footprints. Footprints: list data frames containing footprint coordinates, metadata (e.g., image reference, ID), marker indicating whether footprint actual inferred. test Logical; TRUE, function compares observed intersection metrics . Default FALSE. H1 character string specifying alternative hypothesis tested. Options "Lower" testing whether observed intersections significantly lower simulated ones (e.g., coordinated gregarious movement), "Higher" testing whether observed intersections significantly higher simulated ones (e.g., predatory chasing events). sim track simulation R object consisting list simulated trajectories use comparison test = TRUE. origin.permutation character string specifying method permutation coordinates simulated trajectories' origins. Options include "None", "Min.Box", "Conv.Hull", "Custom". Default "None". custom.coord matrix custom coordinates define vertices area permutation coordinates simulated trajectories' origins.

title: Calculate intersection metrics in tracks — track_intersection
text: track intersection R object consisting list containing following elements: Intersection_metric numeric matrix unique intersection counts trajectories. entry represents number unique intersection points corresponding pair trajectories. Intersection_metric_p_values (test = TRUE) numeric matrix raw pairwise p-values, computed Monte Carlo tail tests according H1, (+1) correction (Phipson & Smyth, 2010): $$p = (1 + \#\{\text{extreme}\}) / (nsim + 1)$$. entry reflects probability observing intersection count extreme observed one, given null hypothesis difference. Intersection_metric_p_values_BH (test = TRUE) numeric matrix Benjamini–Hochberg (BH) adjusted p-values controlling false discovery rate (FDR), applied across set unique pairwise tests (Benjamini & Hochberg, 1995). Intersection_metric_p_values_combined (test = TRUE) single numeric value representing combined p-value across intersections (based global statistic: sum pairwise intersections). indicates overall significance observed intersections relative simulations. Intersection_metric_simulations (test = TRUE) list containing matrices intersection counts simulation iteration, allowing inspection distribution intersections across randomized scenarios.

title: Calculate intersection metrics in tracks — track_intersection
text: track_intersection() function designed calculate number unique intersections trajectories evaluate statistical significance hypothesis testing based simulated tracks. Pairwise p-values computed Monte Carlo tail test according selected alternative hypothesis (H1), using (+1) correction avoid zero-values (see Phipson & Smyth, 2010): $$p = (1 + \#\{\text{extreme}\}) / (nsim + 1)$$ raw p-values adjusted multiple comparisons across set unique pairwise tests using Benjamini–Hochberg (BH) procedure false discovery rate (FDR) control (Benjamini & Hochberg, 1995). raw BH-adjusted p-value matrices returned output object, allowing users inspect either uncorrected corrected results. addition, global combined p-value provided, summarizing overall deviation null across pairs. framework provides robust means comparing observed intersections expected random conditions, intended testing specific behavioral hypotheses related trackmaker interactions. Hypothesis testing controlled H1 argument, defines alternative hypothesis: "Lower": tests whether observed intersections significantly fewer generated simulations. scenario corresponds hypotheses coordinated gregarious movement, parallel group movement result fewer intersections expected random. "Higher": tests whether observed intersections significantly greater generated simulations. scenario corresponds hypotheses predatory chasing interactions, one trackmaker follows crosses another, producing intersections expected random. choice H1 must match biological hypothesis investigation. explicitly specified test = TRUE, error raised. interpretation combined global p-value returned function directly influenced choice H1, determines whether test detects reduction increase intersection counts relative simulated dataset. addition hypothesis testing, track_intersection() function offers several options altering initial positions simulated tracks origin.permutation argument. available options include: "None": Simulated trajectories shifted compared based original starting positions. "Min.Box": Trajectories randomly placed within minimum bounding box surrounding original starting points. "Conv.Hull": Trajectories placed within convex hull encompasses original starting points, providing precise representation area occupied tracks. "Custom": Allows users define specific region interest providing matrix coordinates (custom.coord) specifies vertices desired area. option particularly useful certain spatial features environmental conditions known constrain movement. choice origin.permutation reflect nature behavioral hypothesis tested. example, using "None" appropriate testing intersections compare scenarios trackmakers originate specific locations. contrast, options like "Min.Box", "Conv.Hull", "Custom" suitable evaluating intersections differ tracks originated broader predefined area. track_intersection() function also allows integration similarity metrics computed using simil_DTW_metric() simil_Frechet_metric(). combination intersection counts similarity metrics can provide comprehensive analysis trackmakers interacted, whether movements coordinated independent, whether interactions consistent hypothesized behavioral patterns. Overall, selection H1 origin.permutation carefully considered light specific hypotheses tested. combining intersection metrics similarity measures, users can obtain deeper understanding behavioral dynamics underlying observed trackways.

title: Print track parameters — track_param
text: track_param() function compute print various parameters tracks list track data.

title: Print track parameters — track_param
code: track_param(data)

title: Print track parameters — track_param
text: data track R object, list consisting two elements: Trajectories: list interpolated trajectories, trajectory series midpoints consecutive footprints. Footprints: list data frames containing footprint coordinates, metadata (e.g., image reference, ID), marker indicating whether footprint actual inferred.

title: Print track parameters — track_param
text: list lists, sublist contains computed parameters corresponding track. parameters included : Turning_angles: vector turning angles track (degrees). Mean_turning_angle: mean turning angles (degrees). Standard_deviation_turning_angle: standard deviation turning angles (degrees). Distance: total distance covered track (meters). Length: length track  (meters). Step_lengths: vector step lengths track  (meters). Mean_step_length: mean step lengths  (meters). Standard_deviation_step_length: standard deviation step lengths  (meters). Sinuosity: sinuosity track (dimensionless). Straightness: straightness track (dimensionless). Trackway_width: Mean lateral separation left right footprints (meters), measured perpendicular inferred trackway axis. Pace_angulation: Mean interior angle (degrees) computed alternating triplets (L–R–L R–L–R). reference direction, 0 degrees, considered along positive x-axis. means angles measured counterclockwise positive x-axis, 0 degrees (0 degrees) pointing directly along axis. detailed explanation appropriate methods analyzing circular data, refer Batschelet (1981). Circular mean turning angles computed : $$\bar{θ} = atan2\left(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{=1}^n \sin θ_i, \frac{1}{n}\sum_{=1}^n \cos θ_i\right)$$ : \(θ_i\) \(^{th}\) turning angle radians. \(n\) total number turning angles. \(\sin θ_i\), \(\cos θ_i\) sine cosine components turning angle. \(atan2(y, x)\) two-argument arctangent returns angle correct quadrant. Circular standard deviation turning angles computed : $$s_c = \sqrt{-2 \ln(\bar R)}, \quad \bar R = \sqrt{\left(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{=1}^n \cos θ_i\right)^2 + \left(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{=1}^n \sin θ_i\right)^2}$$ : \(\bar R\) mean resultant length, measuring concentration angles around mean direction. \(n\) total number turning angles. \(\cos θ_i\), \(\sin θ_i\) trigonometric components angle. \(s_c\) circular standard deviation radians (converted degrees function). Sinuosity calculated according Benhamou (2004), defined equation 8. formula used refined version sinuosity index presented Bovet & Benhamou (1988), applicable broader range turning angle distributions require constant step length. sinuosity computed using formula: $$S = 2 \left[ p \left( \frac{1 + c}{1 - c} + b^2 \right) \right]^{-0.5}$$ : \(p\) mean step length (meters), \(c\) mean cosine turning angles (radians), \(b\) coefficient variation step length (meters). straightness index defined ratio D/L, : \(D\) beeline distance first last points trajectory (meters), \(L\) total path length traveled (meters). Straightness index based method described Batschelet (1981). According Benhamou (2004), straightness index serves reliable measure efficiency directed walk. However, suitable random trajectories, index random walk tends towards zero increasing steps. Thus, recommended use measure compare tortuosity random walks consist similar number steps.

title: Print track parameters — track_param
text: function calculates various movement parameters track provided data. uses following helper functions: trajr package: TrajAngles(): Calculates turning angles track. TrajDistance(): Calculates total distance covered track. TrajLength(): Calculates length track. TrajStepLengths(): Calculates step lengths track. TrajSinuosity2(): Calculates sinuosity track. TrajStraightness(): Calculates straightness track. circular package: circular(): Converts raw angles (radians) circular data type. mean.circular(): Computes circular mean turning angles. sd.circular(): Computes circular standard deviation turning angles. circular mean circular standard deviation returned degrees function.

title: Print track parameters — track_param
text: Batschelet, E. (1981). Circular statistics biology. Academic press, 111 Fifth Ave., New York, NY 10003, 1981, 388. Benhamou, S. (2004). reliably estimate tortuosity animal's path:: straightness, sinuosity, fractal dimension?. Journal theoretical biology, 229(2), 209-220. Bovet, P., & Benhamou, S. (1988). Spatial analysis animals' movements using correlated random walk model. Journal theoretical biology, 131(4), 419-433.

what: Calculate velocities and relative stride lengths for tracks — velocity_track
title: Calculate velocities and relative stride lengths for tracks — velocity_track
text: velocity_track() calculates relative stride lengths velocities step series tracks, based step length, height hip, gravity acceleration.

title: Calculate velocities and relative stride lengths for tracks — velocity_track
code: velocity_track(data, H, G = NULL, method = NULL)

title: Calculate velocities and relative stride lengths for tracks — velocity_track
text: data track R object, list consisting two elements: Trajectories: list interpolated trajectories, trajectory series midpoints consecutive footprints. Footprints: list data frames containing footprint coordinates, metadata (e.g., image reference, ID), marker indicating whether footprint actual inferred. H numeric vector representing height hip (meters) track maker. length vector match number tracks data. G Gravity acceleration (meters per second squared). Default 9.8. method character vector specifying method calculate velocities track. Method "" follows approach Alexander (1976), method "B" based Ruiz & Torices (2013). NULL, method "" used tracks.

title: Calculate velocities and relative stride lengths for tracks — velocity_track
text: track velocity R object consisting list lists, sublist contains computed parameters corresponding track. parameters included : Step_velocities: vector velocities step track (meters per second). Mean_velocity: mean velocity across steps track (meters per second). Standard_deviation_velocity: standard deviation velocities across steps track (meters per second). Maximum_velocity: maximum velocity among steps track (meters per second). Minimum_velocity: minimum velocity among steps track (meters per second). Step_relative_stride: vector relative stride lengths step track (dimensionless). Mean_relative_stride: mean relative stride length across steps track (dimensionless). Standard_deviation_relative_stride: standard deviation relative stride lengths across steps track (dimensionless). Maximum_relative_stride: maximum relative stride length among steps track (dimensionless). Minimum_relative_stride: minimum relative stride length among steps track (dimensionless).

title: Calculate velocities and relative stride lengths for tracks — velocity_track
text: velocity_track() estimates speed stride length using classical formulas. shown Prescott et al. (2025), estimates may misleading— particularly tracks produced unconsolidated substrates, actual speeds can substantially lower calculated. Moreover, equal stride lengths may correspond different velocities, conversely, different stride lengths can sometimes reflect similar velocities, depending gait substrate conditions. values therefore treated caution, function subsequent functions incorporate velocity estimates. contrast, trackways formed firmer semi-consolidated surfaces, formulas reliable can provide useful estimates. Use best regarded comparative historical unless substrate context supports confident interpretation. #' velocity_track() function calculates velocities using two methods: Method : Based Alexander (1976), formula: $$v = 0.25 \cdot \sqrt{G} \cdot S^{1.67} \cdot H^{-1.17}$$ v: Velocity track-maker (meters per second). G: Acceleration due gravity (meters per second squared), typically \(9.81\ \text{m/s}^2\). S: Stride length, distance consecutive footprints (meters). H: Height hip track-maker (meters). coefficients \(0.25\), \(1.67\), \(-1.17\) derived empirical studies. coefficients adjust formula account different animal sizes gaits. method applies wide range terrestrial vertebrates used estimate velocity across different gaits. Method B: Based Ruiz & Torices (2013), formula: $$v = 0.226 \cdot \sqrt{G} \cdot S^{1.67} \cdot H^{-1.17}$$ v: Velocity track-maker (meters per second). G: Acceleration due gravity (meters per second squared), typically \(9.81\ \text{m/s}^2\). S: Stride length (meters). H: Height hip track-maker (meters). oefficient \(0.226\) method B refinement based updated data bipedal locomotion. Based Thulborn & Wade (1984), possible identify gaits track-makers basis relative stride length, follows: Walk: \(/H < 2.0\); locomotor performance equivalent walking mammals. Trot: \(2.0 \leq /H \leq 2.9\); locomotor performance equivalent trotting racking mammals. Run: \(/H > 2.9\); locomotor performance equivalent cantering, galloping, sprinting mammals.

title: Calculate velocities and relative stride lengths for tracks — velocity_track

Speed fossil trackways: calculations validated extant birds compliant substrates. Biology Letters, 21(6), 20250191. Ruiz, J., & Torices, . (2013). Humans running stadiums beaches accuracy speed estimations fossil trackways. Ichnos, 20(1), 31-35. Thulborn, R. ., & Wade, M. (1984). Dinosaur trackways Winton Formation (mid-Cretaceous) Queensland. Memoirs Queensland Museum, 21(2), 413-517.
